Anonymous Thu 14 Dec 2023 02:10:16 No.61821478 Report

>>61820970
>More preamble
It needs a rewrite, full stop.

>>61820390
Here's an outline suggestion, just to give you an idea of how to distill the essential elements.

>narrator wakes up
>sees where they are and what they're in is different from what they expected (why? how? answer one or both partially, quickly, and keep the narration moving)
If the narrator is actually a stranger, that should come across in small details
>three natives find the narrator; make it clear, since this is a setting with humans and anthros, what they are
>narrator tries to blend in as native (do they seem to notice? do they buy it? how does the narrator feel about doing this?)
>as narrator travels with characters, drop bits here and there about HOW things in the world are different than the narrator expects (I assume that this is some kind of isekai or unreliable memory thing?)
The repurposed gas station is a detail that can ease the reader into understanding the world + narrator's past. Does the narrator expect the gas station to still be a gas station? Does a gas station being repurposed surprise her for any reason, is it normal to her?
>human is introduced? does the narrator know about humans?

Those are the points I would, based on what you already have, focus on with a rewrite. That or I'd pick a new start point. Maybe a prologue of what the narrator was dreaming/doing? I want to hammer this home, even if you have a mystery in the story, you need to have something clear and obvious for the readers to latch onto in the beginning.

It doesn't look better, it's still obnoxious especially when people speak. It's like opening up a teenage girl's diary and skimming your eyes around without reading, complete with heart symbols in actual spoken dialogue.

It really shows that your experience is writing those captions for images. Well, being brutally honest here, you should throw out any attempt to use your formatting in prose. This is an entirely different stylistic medium.

Prose isn't a comic book or fap captions, tone here is communicated through word choice and placement. A lot of it is left up to the reader's own internal voice and interpretation. Formatting in prose is something that the reader shouldn't notice, because reading is about getting into a flow. Bolded words draw the eye and that's awful when it's not a visual medium. Italics are most often used for a character's internal thoughts.

As for elipses I have to point you and any other new writer towards a resource like
https://www.thepunctuationguide.com/ellipses.html
